# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-turborocket
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] It represents a hybrid class of rocket/ramjet engines, similar to a ramjet, but able to give useful thrust from zero speed, and is also able in some cases to operate outside the atmosphere, with fuel efficiency similar or better than a comparable ramjet or rocket at every point.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] There are a wide variety of variations on the basic concept, and a wide variety of resulting names.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Those that burn additional fuel downstream of the rocket are generally known as ramrockets, rocket-ejector, integral rocket/ramjets or ejector ramjets, whilst those that do not include additional burning are known as ducted rockets or shrouded rockets depending on the details of the expander.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] In a conventional chemical rocket engine, the rocket carries both its fuel and oxidizer in its fuselage.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The chemical reaction between the fuel and the oxidizer produces reactant products which are nominally gases at the pressures and temperatures in the rocket's combustion chamber.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The exhaust is directed rearward through the nozzle, thereby producing a thrust forward.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] In this conventional design, the fuel/oxidizer mixture is both the working mass and energy source that accelerates it.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] It is easy to demonstrate that the best performance is had if the working mass has the lowest molecular weight possible.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Hydrogen, by itself, is the theoretical best rocket fuel.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Mixing this with oxygen in order to burn it lowers the overall performance of the system by raising the mass of the exhaust, as well as greatly increasing the mass that has to be carried aloft – oxygen is much heavier than hydrogen.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] One potential method of increasing the overall performance of the system is to collect either the fuel or the oxidizer during flight.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Fuel is hard to come by in the atmosphere, but oxidizer in the form of gaseous oxygen makes up to 20% of the air.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] There are a number of designs that take advantage of this fact.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] These sorts of systems have been explored in the liquid air cycle engine (LACE).
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Another idea is to collect the working mass.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] With an air-augmented rocket, an otherwise conventional rocket engine is mounted in the center of a long tube, open at the front.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] As the rocket moves through the atmosphere the air enters the front of the tube, where it is compressed via the ram effect.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] As it travels down the tube it is further compressed and mixed with the fuel-rich exhaust from the rocket engine, which heats the air much as a combustor would in a ramjet.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] In this way a fairly small rocket can be used to accelerate a much larger working mass than normal, leading to significantly higher thrust within the atmosphere.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The effectiveness of this simple method can be dramatic.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Typical solid rockets have a specific impulse of about 260 seconds (2.5 kN·s/kg), but using the same fuel in an air-augmented design can improve this to over 500 seconds (4.9 kN·s/kg), a figure unmatched even by high specific impulse hydrolox engines.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] This design can even be slightly more efficient than a ramjet, as the exhaust from the rocket engine helps compress the air more than a ramjet normally would; this raises the combustion efficiency as a longer, more efficient nozzle can be employed.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Another advantage is that the rocket works even at zero forward speed, whereas a ramjet requires forward motion to feed air into the engine.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] It might be envisaged that such an increase in performance would be widely deployed, but various issues frequently preclude this.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The intakes of high-speed engines are difficult to design, and require careful positioning on the airframe in order to achieve reasonable performance – in general, the entire airframe needs to be built around the intake design.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Another problem is that the air thins out as the rocket climbs.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Hence, the amount of additional thrust is limited by how fast the rocket climbs.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Finally, the air ducting adds quite a bit of weight which slows the vehicle considerably towards the end of the burn.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The simplest version of an air-augmentation system is found in the shrouded rocket.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] This consists largely of a rocket motor or motors positioned in a duct.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The rocket exhaust entrains the air, pulling it through the duct, while also mixing with it and heating it, causing the pressure to increase downstream of the rocket.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The resulting hot gas is then further expanded through an expanding nozzle.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] A slight variation on the shrouded rocket, the ducted rocket adds only a convergent-divergent nozzle.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] This ensures the combustion takes place at subsonic speeds, improving the range of vehicle speeds where the system remains useful.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The ejector ramjet is a more complex system with potentially higher performance.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Like the shrouded and ducted rocket, the system begins with a rocket engine(s) in an air intake.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] It differs in that the mixed exhaust enters a diffuser, slowing the speed of the airflow to subsonic speeds.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Additional fuel is then injected, burning in this expanded section.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The exhaust of that combustion then enters a convergent-divergent nozzle as in a conventional ramjet, or the ducted rocket case.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] The first serious attempt to make a production air-augmented rocket was the Soviet Gnom rocket design, implemented by Decree 708-336 of the Soviet Ministers of 2 July 1958.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] More recently, about 2002, NASA has re-examined similar technology for the GTX program as part of an effort to develop SSTO spacecraft.
[src:air-turborocket/air-augmented-rocket] Air-augmented rockets finally entered mass production in 2016 when the Meteor air-to-air missile was introduced into service.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:air-turborocket/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:air-turborocket/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:air-turborocket/atrex] The **ATREX** engine (**Air Turbo Ramjet Engine with eXpander cycle**) developed in Japan is an experimental precooled jet engine that works as a turbojet at low speeds and a ramjet up to mach 6.0.
[src:air-turborocket/atrex] ATREX uses liquid hydrogen fuel in a fairly exotic single-fan arrangement.
[src:air-turborocket/atrex] The liquid hydrogen fuel is pumped through a heat exchanger in the air-intake, simultaneously heating the liquid hydrogen and cooling the incoming air.
[src:air-turborocket/atrex] This cooling of the incoming air is critical in achieving a reasonable efficiency.
[src:air-turborocket/atrex] The hydrogen then continues through a second heat exchanger positioned after the combustion section, where the hot exhaust is used to further heat the hydrogen, turning it in a very high pressure gas.
[src:air-turborocket/atrex] This gas is then passed through the tips of the fan providing driving power to the fan at subsonic speeds.
[src:air-turborocket/atrex] After mixing with the air, the hydrogen is burned in the combustion chamber.
[src:air-turborocket/atrex] The development of this engine lost focus in favor of the new hypersonic precooled turbojet engine (PCTJ).
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] An **axial compressor** is a type of gas compressor that continuously pressurizes a working fluid.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] It is a rotating, airfoil-based device in which the fluid flows primarily in one direction parallel to the axis of rotation.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] This distinguishes axial compressors from other types of rotating compressors, such as centrifugal compressors, axi-centrifugal compressors, and mixed-flow compressors, in which the fluid flowing includes a significant radial component directed outward from the axis of rotation.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The rotor blades exert torque on the fluid, increasing its energy as it passes through the compressor.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The stationary blades, or stators, slow the fluid, converting the circumferential component of flowing into pressure.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Compressors are typically driven by an electric motor, a steam turbine, or a gas turbine.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Axial flow compressors produce a continuous flow of compressed gas.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] They exhibit high efficiency and large mass flow rate in relation to the size of their cross-section.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] They are more intricate and expensive relative to other designs, requiring several rows of airfoils to achieve a large pressure rise.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Axial compressors are integral to the design of large gas turbines such as jet engines, high speed ship engines, and small scale power stations.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] They are also used in industrial applications such as large volume air separation plants, blast furnace air, fluid catalytic cracking air, and propane dehydrogenation.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Additionally, due to their performance and operability across the flight envelope (safe operational limits for an aircraft), they are widely used in aerospace applications.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Axial compressors consist of alternating rows of rotating and stationary airfoils.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The rotating airfoils, or rotors, are mounted on a rotating drum, which is driven by a central shaft.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The stationary airfoils, known as vanes or stators, are mounted to a tubular casing.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] One row of rotors and one row of stators together form a stage.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The rotors impart kinetic energy to the working fluid, increasing its velocity in the axial and circumferential directions.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The stators convert the increased kinetic energy into static pressure through diffusion and redirect the flow direction of the fluid to prepare it for the rotor blades of the next stage.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The area between the rotor drum and casing decreases along the flow direction to maintain an optimum Mach number as the fluid is compressed.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Rotor passages can be designed to achieve diffusive pressure rise, leading to a higher pressure rise per stage.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The ratio of pressure rise in the rotor to the total pressure rise of the stage is known as the degree of reaction.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The increase in pressure produced by a single stage is limited by the relative velocity between the rotor and the fluid, and the turning and diffusion capabilities of the airfoils.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] A typical stage in a commercial compressor will produce a pressure increase of between 15% and 60% (pressure ratios of 1.15–1.6) at design conditions with a polytropic efficiency in the region of 90–95%.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] To achieve different pressure ratios, axial compressors are designed with different numbers of stages and rotational speeds.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] As a rule of thumb, it can be assumed that each stage in a given compressor has the same temperature rise (ΔT).
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Therefore, at the entry, temperature (Tstage) to each stage must increase progressively through the compressor and the ratio (Delta T)/(Tstage) entry must decrease, thus implying a progressive reduction in stage pressure ratio through the unit.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Hence the rear stage develops a significantly lower pressure ratio than the first stage.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Higher stage pressure ratios are also possible if the relative velocity between fluid and rotors is supersonic, but this is achieved at the expense of efficiency and operability.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Such compressors, with stage pressure ratios of over 2, are only used where minimizing the compressor size, weight or complexity is critical, such as in military jets.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The airfoil profiles are optimized and matched for specific velocities and turning.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Although compressors can be run at other conditions with different flows, speeds, or pressure ratios, this can result in an efficiency penalty or even a partial or complete breakdown in flow (known as compressor stall and pressure surge respectively).
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Thus, a practical limit on the number of stages, and the overall pressure ratio, comes from the interaction of the different stages when required to work away from the design conditions.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] These "off-design" conditions can be mitigated to a certain extent by providing some flexibility in the compressor.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] This is achieved normally through the use of adjustable stators or with valves that can bleed fluid from the main flow between stages (inter-stage bleed).
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Modern jet engines use a series of compressors, running at different speeds; to supply air at around 40:1 pressure ratio for combustion with sufficient flexibility for all flight conditions.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The law of moment of momentum states that the sum of the moments of external forces acting on a fluid which is temporarily occupying the control volume is equal to the net change of angular momentum flux through the control volume.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The swirling fluid enters the control volume at radius, $r_{1}\,$ , with tangential velocity, $V_{w1}\,$ , and leaves at radius, $r_{2}\,$ , with tangential velocity, $V_{w2}\,$ .
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] are the absolute velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] are the axial flow velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] are the swirl velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] are the blade-relative velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Axial compressor performance is shown on a compressor map, also known as a characteristic, by plotting pressure ratio and efficiency against corrected mass flow at different values of corrected compressor speed.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Axial compressors, particularly near their design point are usually amenable to analytical treatment, and a good estimate of their performance can be made before they are first run on a rig.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The compressor map shows the complete running range, i.e. off-design, of the compressor from ground idle to its highest corrected rotor speed, which for a civil engine may occur at top-of-climb, or, for a military combat engine, at take-off on a cold day.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Not shown is the sub-idle performance region needed for analysing normal ground and in-flight windmill start behaviour.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Stage pressure ratio against flow rate is lower than for a no-loss stage as shown.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Losses are due to blade friction, flow separation, unsteady flow and vane-blade spacing.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The performance of a compressor is defined according to its design.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] But in actual practice, the operating point of the compressor deviates from the design point; this is known as *off-design operation*.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The value of $(\tan \beta _{2}+\tan \alpha _{1})\,$ doesn't change for a wide range of operating points till stalling.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Also $\alpha _{1}=\alpha _{3}\,$ because of minor change in air angle at rotor and stator, where $\alpha _{3}\,$ is diffuser blade angle.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] for positive values of J, slope of the curve is negative and vice versa.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] There are multiple modes of instability an axial compressor could undergo.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Edward Greitzer used a Helmholtz resonator type of compression system model to predict the transient response of a compression system after a small perturbation superimposed on a steady operating condition.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] He found a non-dimensional parameter which predicted which mode of compressor instability, rotating stall or surge, would result.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The parameter used the rotor speed, the Helmholtz resonator frequency of the system, and an "effective length" of the compressor duct.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] These produced a critical value which predicted either rotating stall or surge where the slope of pressure ratio against flow changed from negative to positive.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In the plot of pressure-flow rate, the line separating graph between two regions – unstable and stable – is known as the **surge line**.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] This line is formed by joining surge points at different rotational speeds.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Surging is the unstable flow in axial compressors due to complete breakdown of the steady through flow.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] This phenomenon affects the performance of compressor and is undesirable.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The following explanation for surging refers to running a compressor at a constant speed on a rig and gradually reducing the exit area by closing a valve.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] What happens, i.e. crossing the surge line, is caused by the compressor trying to deliver air, still running at the same speed, to a higher exit pressure.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Suppose the initial operating point *D* ( ${\dot {m}},P_{D}\,$ ) at some rotational speed *N*.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] On decreasing the flow-rate at same rotational speed along the characteristic curve by partial closing of the valve, the pressure in the pipe increases which will be taken care by increase in input pressure at the compressor.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] With further increase in pressure up to point *P* (surge point), compressor pressure will increase.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Further moving towards left keeping rotational speed constant, pressure in pipe will increase but compressor pressure will decrease leading to back air flow towards the compressor.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Due to this back flow, pressure in pipe will decrease because this unequal pressure condition cannot stay for a long period of time.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Though valve position is set for lower flow rate say point *G* but compressor will work according to normal stable operation point say *E*, so path *E*–*F*–*P*–*G*–*E* will be followed leading to breakdown of flow, hence pressure in the compressor falls further to point *H*( $P_{H}\,$ ).
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] This increase and decrease of pressure in pipe will occur repeatedly in pipe and compressor following the cycle *E*–*F*–*P*–*G*–*H*–*E* also known as the surge cycle.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] This phenomenon will cause vibrations in the whole machine and may lead to mechanical failure.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] That is why left portion of the curve from the surge point is called unstable region and may cause damage to the machine.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] So the recommended operation range is on the right side of the surge line.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Stall is a phenomenon affecting the performance of the compressor whereby flow separation occurs at the compressor blades, leading to reduced compression and a drop in engine power.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] An analysis is made of rotating stall in compressors of many stages, finding conditions under which a flow distortion can occur which is steady in a traveling reference frame, even though upstream total and downstream static pressure are constant.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In the compressor, a pressure-rise hysteresis is assumed.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Two types of stall are distinguished: *positive stall,* where flow separation occurs on the suction side of the blade, and *negative stall,* where it occurs on the pressure side.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In practice, negative stall is negligible compared to positive stall as flow separation is least likely to occur on the pressure side of the blade.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In a multi-stage compressor, at the high pressure stages, axial velocity is very small.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Stalling value decreases with a small deviation from the design point causing stall near the hub and tip regions whose size increases with decreasing flow rates.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] They grow larger at very low flow rate and affect the entire blade height.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Non-uniformity of air flow in the rotor blades may disturb local air flow in the compressor without upsetting it.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The compressor continues to work normally but with reduced compression.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Thus, rotating stall decreases the effectiveness of the compressor.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In a rotor with blades moving say towards right.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Let some blades receives flow at higher incidence, this blade will stop positively.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] It creates obstruction in the passage between the blade to its left and itself.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Thus the left blade will receive the flow at higher incidence and the blade to its right with decreased incidence.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The left blade will experience more stall while the blade to its right will experience lesser stall.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Towards the right stalling will decrease whereas it will increase towards its left.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Movement of the rotating stall can be observed depending upon the chosen reference frame.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] From an energy exchange point of view axial compressors are reversed turbines.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Steam-turbine designer Charles Algernon Parsons, for example, recognized that a turbine which produced work by virtue of a fluid's static pressure (i.e. a reaction turbine) could have its action reversed to act as an air compressor, calling it a turbo compressor or pump.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] His rotor and stator blading described in one of his patents had little or no camber although in some cases the blade design was based on propeller theory.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The machines, driven by steam turbines, were used for industrial purposes such as supplying air to blast furnaces.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Parsons supplied the first commercial axial flow compressor for use in a lead smelter in 1901.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Parsons' machines had low efficiencies, later attributed to blade stall, and were soon replaced with more efficient centrifugal compressors.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Brown Boveri & Cie produced "reversed turbine" compressors, driven by gas turbines, with blading derived from aerodynamic research which were more efficient than centrifugal types when pumping large flow rates of 40,000 ft3/min (19 m3/s) at pressures up to 45 psi (310 kPa).
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Because early axial compressors were not efficient enough a number of papers in the early 1920s claimed that a practical axial-flow turbojet engine would be impossible to construct.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Griffith published a seminal paper in 1926, noting that the reason for the poor performance was that existing compressors used flat blades and were essentially "flying stalled".
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] He showed that the use of airfoils instead of the flat blades would increase efficiency to the point where a practical jet engine was a real possibility.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] He concluded the paper with a basic diagram of such an engine, which included a second turbine that was used to power a propeller.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Although Griffith was well known due to his earlier work on metal fatigue and stress measurement, little work appears to have started as a direct result of his paper.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The only obvious effort was a test-bed compressor built by Hayne Constant, Griffith's colleague at the Royal Aircraft Establishment.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Other early jet efforts, notably those of Frank Whittle and Hans von Ohain, were based on the more robust and better understood centrifugal compressor which was widely used in superchargers.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Griffith had seen Whittle's work in 1929 and dismissed it, noting a mathematical error, and going on to claim that the frontal size of the engine would make it useless on a high-speed aircraft.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Real work on axial-flow engines started in the late 1930s, in several efforts that all started at about the same time.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In England, Hayne Constant reached an agreement with the steam turbine company Metropolitan-Vickers (Metrovick) in 1937, starting their turboprop effort based on the Griffith design in 1938.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In 1940, after the successful run of Whittle's centrifugal-flow design, their effort was re-designed as a pure jet, the Metrovick F.2.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In the United States, both Lockheed and General Electric were awarded contracts in 1941 to develop axial-flow engines, the former a pure jet, the latter a turboprop.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Northrop also started their own project to develop a turboprop, which the US Navy eventually contracted in 1943.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Westinghouse also entered the race in 1942, their project proving to be the only successful one of the US efforts, later becoming the J30.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] As Griffith had originally noted in 1929, the large frontal size of the centrifugal compressor caused it to have higher drag than the narrower axial-flow type.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Additionally the axial-flow design could improve its compression ratio simply by adding additional stages and making the engine slightly longer.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In the centrifugal-flow design the compressor itself had to be larger in diameter, which was much more difficult to fit properly into a thin and aerodynamic aircraft fuselage (although not dissimilar to the profile of radial engines already in widespread use).
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] On the other hand, centrifugal-flow designs remained much less complex (the major reason they "won" in the race to flying examples) and therefore have a role in places where size and streamlining are not so important.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In the jet engine application, the compressor faces a wide variety of operating conditions.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] On the ground at high power settings the inlet pressure is high, inlet speed zero, and the compressor spun at a variety of speeds as the power is applied.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Once in flight the inlet pressure drops, but the inlet speed increases (due to the forward motion of the aircraft) to recover some of this pressure, and the compressor tends to run at a single speed for long periods of time.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] There is simply no "perfect" compressor for this wide range of operating conditions.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Fixed geometry compressors, like those used on early jet engines, are limited to a design pressure ratio of about 4:1 or 5:1.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] As with any heat engine, fuel efficiency is strongly related to the compression ratio, so there is very strong financial need to improve the compressor stages beyond these sorts of ratios.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Additionally the compressor may stall if the inlet conditions change abruptly, a common problem on early engines.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In some cases, if the stall occurs near the front of the engine, all of the stages from that point on will stop compressing the air.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In this situation the energy required to run the compressor drops suddenly, and the remaining hot air in the rear of the engine allows the turbine to speed up the whole engine dramatically.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] This condition, known as surging, was a major problem on early engines and often led to the turbine or compressor breaking and shedding blades.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] For all of these reasons, axial compressors on modern jet engines are considerably more complex than those on earlier designs.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] All compressors have an optimum point relating rotational speed and pressure, with higher compressions requiring higher speeds.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Early engines were designed for simplicity, and used a single large compressor spinning at a single speed.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Later designs added a second turbine and divided the compressor into low-pressure and high-pressure sections, the latter spinning faster.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] This *two-spool* design, pioneered on the Bristol Olympus, resulted in increased efficiency.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Further increases in efficiency may be realised by adding a third spool, but in practice the added complexity increases maintenance costs to the point of negating any economic benefit.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] That said, there are several three-spool engines in use, perhaps the most famous being the Rolls-Royce RB211 (and its successor, the Rolls-Royce Trent), used on a wide variety of commercial aircraft.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] As an aircraft changes speed or altitude, the pressure of the air at the inlet to the compressor will vary.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] In order to "tune" the compressor for these changing conditions, designs starting in the 1950s would "bleed" air out of the middle of the compressor in order to avoid trying to compress too much air in the final stages.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] This was also used to help start the engine, allowing it to be spun up without compressing much air by bleeding off as much as possible.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Bleed systems were already commonly used anyway, to provide airflow into the turbine stage where it was used to cool the turbine blades, as well as provide pressurized air for the air conditioning systems inside the aircraft.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] A more advanced design, the *variable stator*, used blades that can be individually rotated around their axis, as opposed to the power axis of the engine.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] For start up they are rotated to "closed", reducing compression, and then are rotated back into the airflow as the external conditions require.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The General Electric J79 was the first major example of a variable stator design, and today it is a common feature of most military engines.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Closing the variable stators progressively, as compressor speed falls, reduces the slope of the surge (or stall) line on the operating characteristic (or map), improving the surge margin of the installed unit.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] By incorporating variable stators in the first five stages, General Electric Aircraft Engines has developed a ten-stage axial compressor capable of operating at a 23:1 design pressure ratio.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The relative motion of the blades to the fluid adds velocity or pressure or both to the fluid as it passes through the rotor.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The fluid velocity is increased through the rotor, and the stator converts kinetic energy to pressure energy.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Some diffusion also occurs in the rotor in most practical designs.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The increase in velocity of the fluid is primarily in the tangential direction (swirl) and the stator removes this angular momentum.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The pressure rise results in a stagnation temperature rise.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] For a given geometry the temperature rise depends on the square of the tangential Mach number of the rotor row.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Current turbofan engines have fans that operate at Mach 1.7 or more, and require significant containment and noise suppression structures to reduce blade loss damage and noise.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] A map shows the performance of a compressor and allows determination of optimal operating conditions.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] It shows the mass flow along the horizontal axis, typically as a percentage of the design mass flow rate, or in actual units.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] The pressure rise is indicated on the vertical axis as a ratio between inlet and exit stagnation pressures.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] A surge or stall line identifies the boundary to the left of which the compressor performance rapidly degrades and identifies the maximum pressure ratio that can be achieved for a given mass flow.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Contours of efficiency are drawn as well as performance lines for operation at particular rotational speeds.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Operating efficiency is highest close to the stall line.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] If the downstream pressure is increased beyond the maximum possible the compressor will stall and become unstable.
[src:air-turborocket/axial-compressor] Typically the instability will be at the Helmholtz frequency of the system, taking the downstream plenum into account.
[src:air-turborocket/brandner-e-300] The **Brandner E-300** was an Egyptian turbojet engine, developed for the Helwan HA-300 light jet fighter.
[src:air-turborocket/brandner-e-300] The new engine underwent bench testing in 1963, and was flight tested under the wing of an Antonov An-12, before being installed in a HAL HF-24 Marut for high speed testing, in which form it flew on 29 March 1967.
[src:air-turborocket/brandner-e-300] The E-300 was installed in the third HA-300 prototype (the first two were powered by Bristol Siddeley Orpheus engines), but testing stopped in the taxi-test stage before flight tests.
[src:air-turborocket/brandner-e-300] The programme of HA-300 was abandoned in May 1969.
[src:air-turborocket/brandner-e-300] Civil version of E-300-A, proposed for Project 206 three-engined airliner.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] A **combustor** is a component or area of a gas turbine, ramjet, or scramjet engine where combustion takes place.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] It is also known as a **burner**, **burner can**, **combustion chamber** or **flame holder**.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] In a gas turbine engine, the *combustor* or combustion chamber is fed high-pressure air by the compression system.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The combustor then heats this air at constant pressure as the fuel/air mix burns.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] As it burns the fuel/air mix heats and rapidly expands.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The burned mix is exhausted from the combustor through the nozzle guide vanes to the turbine.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] In the case of ramjet or scramjet engines, the exhaust is directly fed out through the nozzle.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] A combustor must contain and maintain stable combustion despite very high air flow rates.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] To do so combustors are carefully designed to first mix and ignite the air and fuel, and then mix in more air to complete the combustion process.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Early gas turbine engines used a single chamber known as a can-type combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Today three main configurations exist: can, annular, and cannular (also referred to as can-annular tubo-annular).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Afterburners are often considered another type of combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Combustors play a crucial role in determining many of an engine's operating characteristics, such as fuel efficiency, levels of emissions, and transient response (the response to changing conditions such as fuel flow and air speed).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The objective of the combustor in a gas turbine is to add energy to the system to power the turbines, and produce a high-velocity gas to exhaust through the nozzle in aircraft applications.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Advancements in combustor technology focused on several distinct areas; emissions, operating range, and durability.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Early jet engines produced large amounts of smoke, so early combustor advances, in the 1950s, were aimed at reducing the smoke produced by the engine.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Once smoke was essentially eliminated, efforts turned in the 1970s to reducing other emissions, like unburned hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide (for more details, see § Emissions).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The 1970s also saw improvement in combustor durability, as new manufacturing methods improved liner (see § Components) lifetime by nearly 100 times that of early liners.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] In the 1980s combustors began to improve their efficiency across the whole operating range; combustors tended to be highly efficient (>99%) at full power, but that efficiency dropped off at lower settings.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Development over that decade improved efficiencies at lower levels.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The 1990s and 2000s saw a renewed focus on reducing emissions, particularly nitrogen oxides.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Combustor technology is still being actively researched and advanced, and much modern research focuses on improving the same aspects.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The case is the outer shell of the combustor, and is a fairly simple structure.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The casing generally requires little maintenance.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The case is protected from thermal loads by the air flowing in it, so thermal performance is of limited concern.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] However, the casing serves as a pressure vessel that must withstand the difference between the high pressures inside the combustor and the lower pressure outside.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] That mechanical (rather than thermal) load is a driving design factor in the case.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The purpose of the diffuser is to slow the high-speed, highly compressed, air from the compressor to a velocity optimal for the combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Reducing the velocity results in an unavoidable loss in total pressure, so one of the design challenges is to limit the loss of pressure as much as possible.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Furthermore, the diffuser must be designed to limit the flow distortion as much as possible by avoiding flow effects like boundary layer separation.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Like most other gas turbine engine components, the diffuser is designed to be as short and light as possible.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The liner contains the combustion process and introduces the various airflows (intermediate, dilution, and cooling, see § Air flow paths) into the combustion zone.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The liner must be designed and built to withstand extended high-temperature cycles.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] For that reason liners tend to be made from superalloys like Hastelloy X.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Furthermore, even though high-performance alloys are used, the liners must be cooled with air flow.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Some combustors also make use of thermal barrier coatings.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] In general, there are two main types of liner cooling; film cooling and transpiration cooling.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Film cooling works by injecting (by one of several methods) cool air from outside of the liner to just inside of the liner.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This creates a thin film of cool air that protects the liner, reducing the temperature at the liner from around 1800 kelvins (K) to around 830 K, for example.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The other type of liner cooling, transpiration cooling, is a more modern approach that uses a porous material for the liner.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The porous liner allows a small amount of cooling air to pass through it, providing cooling benefits similar to film cooling.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The two primary differences are in the resulting temperature profile of the liner and the amount of cooling air required.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Transpiration cooling results in a much more even temperature profile, as the cooling air is uniformly introduced through pores.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Film cooling air is generally introduced through slats or louvers, resulting in an uneven profile where it is cooler at the slat and warmer between the slats.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] More importantly, transpiration cooling uses much less cooling air (on the order of 10% of total airflow, rather than 20–50% for film cooling).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Using less air for cooling allows more to be used for combustion, which is more and more important for high-performance, high-thrust engines.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The snout is an extension of the dome (see below) that acts as an air splitter, separating the primary air from the secondary air flows (intermediate, dilution, and cooling air; see § Air flow paths).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The dome and swirler are the part of the combustor that the primary air (see § Air flow paths) flows through as it enters the combustion zone.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Their role is to generate turbulence in the flow to rapidly mix the air with fuel.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Early combustors tended to use *bluff body domes* (rather than swirlers), which used a simple plate to create wake turbulence to mix the fuel and air.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Most modern designs, however, are *swirl stabilized* (use swirlers).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The swirler establishes a local low pressure zone that forces some of the combustion products to recirculate, creating the high turbulence.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] However, the higher the turbulence, the higher the pressure loss will be for the combustor, so the dome and swirler must be carefully designed so as not to generate more turbulence than is needed to sufficiently mix the fuel and air.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The fuel injector is responsible for introducing fuel to the combustion zone and, along with the swirler (above), is responsible for mixing the fuel and air.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] There are four primary types of fuel injectors; pressure-atomizing, air blast, vaporizing, and premix/prevaporizing injectors.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Pressure atomizing fuel injectors rely on high fuel pressures (as much as 3,400 kilopascals (500 psi)) to atomize the fuel.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This type of fuel injector has the advantage of being very simple, but it has several disadvantages.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The fuel system must be robust enough to withstand such high pressures, and the fuel tends to be heterogeneously atomized, resulting in incomplete or uneven combustion which has more pollutants and smoke.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The second type of fuel injector is the air blast injector.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This injector "blasts" a sheet of fuel with a stream of air, atomizing the fuel into homogeneous droplets.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This type of fuel injector led to the first smokeless combustors.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The air used is just some of the primary air (see § Air flow paths) that is diverted through the injector, rather than the swirler.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This type of injector also requires lower fuel pressures than the pressure atomizing type.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The vaporizing fuel injector, the third type, is similar to the air blast injector in that primary air is mixed with the fuel as it is injected into the combustion zone.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] However, the fuel-air mixture travels through a tube within the combustion zone.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Heat from the combustion zone is transferred to the fuel-air mixture, vaporizing some of the fuel (mixing it better) before it is combusted.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This method allows the fuel to be combusted with less thermal radiation, which helps protect the liner.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] However, the vaporizer tube may have serious durability problems with low fuel flow within it (the fuel inside of the tube protects the tube from the combustion heat).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The premixing/prevaporizing injectors work by mixing or vaporizing the fuel before it reaches the combustion zone.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This method allows the fuel to be very uniformly mixed with the air, reducing emissions from the engine.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] One disadvantage of this method is that fuel may auto-ignite or otherwise combust before the fuel-air mixture reaches the combustion zone.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] If this happens the combustor can be seriously damaged.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Most igniters in gas turbine applications are electrical spark igniters, similar to automotive spark plugs.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The igniter needs to be in the combustion zone where the fuel and air are already mixed, but it needs to be far enough upstream so that it is not damaged by the combustion itself.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Once the combustion is initially started by the igniter, it is self-sustaining, and the igniter is no longer used.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] In can-annular and annular combustors (see § Types of combustors), the flame can propagate from one combustion zone to another, so igniters are not needed at each one.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] In some systems ignition-assist techniques are used.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] One such method is oxygen injection, where oxygen is fed to the ignition area, helping the fuel easily combust.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This is particularly useful in some aircraft applications where the engine may have to restart at high altitude.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] It is highly compressed air from the high-pressure compressor (often decelerated via the diffuser) that is fed through the main channels in the dome of the combustor and the first set of liner holes.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This air is mixed with fuel, and then combusted.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Intermediate air is the air injected into the combustion zone through the second set of liner holes (primary air goes through the first set).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This air completes the reaction processes, diluting the high concentrations of carbon monoxide (CO) and hydrogen (H2), and also helps cooling down the gases from combustion.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Dilution air is air injected through holes in the liner at the end of the combustion chamber to cool the flue gas before it reaches the turbines.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The air is carefully used to produce the uniform temperature profile desired in the combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] However, as turbine blade technology improves, allowing them to withstand higher temperatures, dilution air is used less, allowing the use of more combustion air.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Cooling air is air that is injected through small holes in the liner to generate a layer (film) of cool air to protect the liner from the combustion temperatures.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The implementation of cooling air has to be carefully designed so it does not directly interact with the combustion air and process.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] In some cases, as much as 50% of the inlet air is used as cooling air.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] There are several different methods of injecting this cooling air, and the method can influence the temperature profile that the liner is exposed to (see § Liner).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Can combustors are self-contained cylindrical combustion chambers.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Each "can" has its own fuel injector, igniter, liner, and casing.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The primary air from the compressor is guided into each individual can, where it is decelerated, mixed with fuel, and then ignited.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The secondary air also comes from the compressor, where it is fed outside of the liner (inside of which is where the combustion is taking place).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The secondary air is then fed, usually through slits in the liner, into the combustion zone to cool the liner via thin film cooling.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] In most applications, multiple cans are arranged around the central axis of the engine, and their shared exhaust is fed to the turbine(s).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Can-type combustors were most widely used in early gas turbine engines, owing to their ease of design and testing (one can test a single can, rather than have to test the whole system).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Can-type combustors are easy to maintain, as only a single can needs to be removed, rather than the whole combustion section.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Most modern gas turbine engines (particularly for aircraft applications) do not use can combustors, as they often weigh more than alternatives.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Additionally, the pressure drop across the can is generally higher than other combustors (on the order of 7%).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Most modern engines that use can combustors are turboshafts featuring centrifugal compressors.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The next type of combustor is the "can-annular" combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Like the can-type combustor, can-annular combustors have discrete combustion zones contained in separate liners with their own fuel injectors.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Unlike the can combustor, all the combustion zones share a common ring (annulus) casing.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Each combustion zone no longer has to serve as a pressure vessel.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The combustion zones can also "communicate" with each other via liner holes or connecting tubes that allow some air to flow circumferentially.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The exit flow from the can-annular combustor generally has a more uniform temperature profile, which is better for the turbine section.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] It also eliminates the need for each chamber to have its own igniter.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Once the fire is lit in one or two cans, it can easily spread to and ignite the others.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This type of combustor is also lighter than the can type, and has a lower pressure drop (on the order of 6%).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] However, a can-annular combustor can be more difficult to maintain than a can combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Examples of gas turbine engines utilizing a can-annular combustor include both turbojets like the General Electric J79 and turbofans like the Pratt & Whitney TF30 and Rolls-Royce Tay.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The final, and most-commonly used type of combustor is the fully annular combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Annular combustors do away with the separate combustion zones and simply have a continuous liner and casing in a ring (the annulus).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] There are many advantages to annular combustors, including more uniform combustion, shorter size (therefore lighter), and less surface area.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Additionally, annular combustors tend to have very uniform exit temperatures.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] They also have the lowest pressure drop of the three designs (on the order of 5%).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The annular design is also simpler, although testing generally requires a full size test rig.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Engines that use an annular combustor include the CFM International CFM56, the General Electric F110 and the Pratt & Whitney F401.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Almost all of the modern gas turbine engines use annular combustors; likewise, most combustor research and development focuses on improving this type.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] One variation on the standard annular combustor is the *double annular combustor* (DAC).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Like an annular combustor, the DAC is a continuous ring without separate combustion zones around the radius.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The difference is that the combustor has two combustion zones around the ring; a pilot zone and a main zone.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The pilot zone acts like that of a single annular combustor, and is the only zone operating at low power levels.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] At high power levels, the main zone is used as well, increasing air and mass flow through the combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] GE's implementation of this type of combustor focuses on reducing NO*x* and CO2 emissions.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] A good diagram of a DAC is available from Purdue.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Extending the same principles as the double annular combustor, triple annular and "multiple annular" combustors have been proposed and even patented.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] One of the driving factors in modern gas turbine design is reducing emissions, and the combustor is the primary contributor to a gas turbine's emissions.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Generally speaking, there are five major types of emissions from gas turbine engines: smoke, carbon dioxide (CO2), carbon monoxide (CO), unburned hydrocarbons (UHC), and nitrogen oxides (NOx).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Smoke is primarily mitigated by more evenly mixing the fuel with air.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] As discussed in the fuel injector section above, modern fuel injectors (such as airblast fuel injectors) evenly atomize the fuel and eliminate local pockets of high fuel concentration.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Most modern engines use these types of fuel injectors and are essentially smokeless.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Carbon dioxide is a product of the combustion process, and it is primarily mitigated by reducing fuel usage.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] On average, 1 kg of jet fuel burned produces 3.2 kg of CO2.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Carbon dioxide emissions will continue to drop as manufacturers improve the overall efficiency of gas turbine engines.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Unburned-hydrocarbon (UHC) and carbon-monoxide (CO) emissions are highly related.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] UHCs are essentially fuel that was not completely combusted.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] They are mostly produced at low power levels (where the engine is not burning all the fuel).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Much of the UHC content reacts and forms CO within the combustor, which is why the two types of emissions are heavily related.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] As a result of this close relation, a combustor that is well optimized for CO emissions is inherently well optimized for UHC emissions, so most design work focuses on CO emissions.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Carbon monoxide is an intermediate product of combustion, and it is eliminated by oxidation.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This process, which consumes the CO, requires a relatively long time ("relatively" is used because the combustion process happens incredibly quickly), high temperatures, and high pressures.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This fact means that a low-CO combustor has a long *residence time* (essentially the amount of time the gases are in the combustion chamber).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Like CO, Nitrogen oxides (NOx) are produced in the combustion zone.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] However, unlike CO, it is most produced during the conditions that CO is most consumed (high temperature, high pressure, long residence time).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This means that, in general, reducing CO emissions results in an increase in NOx, and vice versa.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This fact means that most successful emission reductions require the combination of several methods.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] An afterburner (or reheat) is an additional component added to some jet engines, primarily those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Its purpose is to provide a temporary increase in thrust, both for supersonic flight and for takeoff (as the high wing loading typical of supersonic aircraft designs means that take-off speed is very high).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] On military aircraft the extra thrust is also useful for combat situations.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This is achieved by injecting additional fuel into the jet pipe downstream of (i.e.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The advantage of afterburning is significantly increased thrust; the disadvantage is its very high fuel consumption and inefficiency, though this is often regarded as acceptable for the short periods during which it is usually used.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning is being used and *dry* when the engine is used without afterburning.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power* or *max reheat* (this is the maximum power the engine can produce); an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power* or *max dry*.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] As with the main combustor in a gas turbine, the afterburner has both a case and a liner, serving the same purpose as their main combustor counterparts.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] One major difference between a main combustor and an afterburner is that the temperature rise is not constrained by a turbine section, therefore afterburners tend to have a much higher temperature rise than main combustors.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Another difference is that afterburners are not designed to mix fuel as well as primary combustors, so not all the fuel is burned within the afterburner section.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Afterburners also often require the use of flameholders to keep the velocity of the air in the afterburner from blowing the flame out.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] These are often bluff bodies or "vee-gutters" directly behind the fuel injectors that create localized low-speed flow in the same manner the dome does in the main combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Ramjet engines differ in many ways from traditional gas turbine engines, but most of the same principles hold.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] One major difference is the lack of rotating machinery (a turbine) after the combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] The combustor exhaust is directly fed to a nozzle.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] This allows ramjet combustors to burn at a higher temperature.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Another difference is that many ramjet combustors do not use liners like gas turbine combustors do.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Furthermore, some ramjet combustors are *dump combustors* rather than a more conventional type.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Dump combustors inject fuel and rely on recirculation generated by a large change in area in the combustor (rather than swirlers in many gas turbine combustors).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] That said, many ramjet combustors are also similar to traditional gas turbine combustors, such as the combustor in the ramjet used by the RIM-8 Talos missile, which used a can-type combustor.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] Scramjet (*supersonic combustion ramjet*) engines present a much different situation for the combustor than conventional gas turbine engines (scramjets are not gas turbines, as they generally have few or no moving parts).
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] While scramjet combustors may be physically quite different from conventional combustors, they face many of the same design challenges, like fuel mixing and flame holding.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] However, as its name implies, a scramjet combustor must address these challenges in a supersonic flow environment.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] For example, for a scramjet flying at Mach 5, the air flow entering the combustor would nominally be Mach 2.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] One of the major challenges in a scramjet engine is preventing shock waves generated by combustor from traveling upstream into the inlet.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] If that were to happen, the engine may unstart, resulting in loss of thrust, among other problems.
[src:air-turborocket/combustor] To prevent this, scramjet engines tend to have an isolator section (see image) immediately ahead of the combustion zone.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] A **de Laval nozzle** (or **convergent–divergent nozzle**, **CD nozzle** or **con–di nozzle**) is a tube that is pinched in the middle with a rapid convergence and gradual divergence.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] It is used to accelerate a compressible fluid to supersonic speeds in the axial (thrust) direction, by converting the thermal energy of the flow into kinetic energy.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] De Laval nozzles are widely used in some types of steam turbines and rocket engine nozzles.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] It also sees use in supersonic jet engines.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] Similar flow properties have been applied to jet streams in astrophysics.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] Giovanni Battista Venturi designed converging–diverging tubes known as Venturi tubes for experiments on fluid pressure reduction effects when fluid flows through chokes (Venturi effect).
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] German engineer and inventor Ernst Körting supposedly switched to a converging–diverging nozzle in his steam jet pumps by 1878 after using convergent nozzles, but these nozzles remained a company secret.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] In 1888, Swedish engineer Gustaf de Laval designed a converging–diverging nozzle design for his impulse turbine.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] Laval's convergent–divergent nozzle was first applied in a rocket engine by Robert Goddard.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] Most modern rocket engines that employ hot gas combustion use de Laval nozzles.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] A de Laval nozzle's operation relies on the different properties of gases flowing at subsonic, sonic, and supersonic speeds.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] The speed of a subsonic flow of gas will increase if the pipe carrying it narrows because the mass flow rate is constant.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] The gas flow through a de Laval nozzle is isentropic—that is, gas entropy is nearly constant.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] In a subsonic flow, sound will propagate through the gas.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] At the "throat", where the cross-sectional area is at its minimum, the gas velocity locally becomes sonic (Mach number = 1.0), a condition called choked flow.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] As the nozzle cross-sectional area increases, the gas begins to expand, and the flow increases to supersonic velocities, where a sound wave will not propagate backward through the gas as viewed in the frame of reference of the nozzle (Mach number > 1.0).
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] A de Laval nozzle will choke at the throat only if the pressure and mass flow through the nozzle is sufficient to reach sonic speeds; otherwise no supersonic flow is achieved, and it will act as a Venturi tube.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] This requires the entry pressure to the nozzle to be significantly above ambient at all times (equivalently, the stagnation pressure of the jet must be above ambient).
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] In addition, the pressure of the gas at the exit of the expansion portion of the exhaust of a nozzle must not be too low.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] In practice, ambient pressure must be no higher than roughly two to three times the pressure in the supersonic gas at the exit for supersonic flow to leave the nozzle.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] As the gas enters a nozzle, it is moving at subsonic velocities.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] As the cross-sectional area contracts, the gas is forced to accelerate until the axial velocity becomes sonic at the nozzle throat, where the cross-sectional area is the smallest.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] From there the throat cross-sectional area then increases, allowing the gas to expand and the axial velocity to become progressively more supersonic.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] As a note of interest, *v*e is sometimes referred to as the *ideal exhaust gas velocity* because it is based on the assumption that the exhaust gas behaves as an ideal gas.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] Using those values in the above equation yields an exhaust velocity *v*e = 2802 m/s, or 2.80 km/s, which is consistent with above typical values.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] Technical literature often interchanges without note the universal gas law constant *R*, which applies to any ideal gas, with the gas law constant *Rs*, which applies only to a specific individual gas of molar mass *M*.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] The relationship between the two constants is *Rs* = *R/M*.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] In accordance with conservation of mass the mass flow rate of the gas throughout the nozzle is the same regardless of the cross-sectional area.
[src:air-turborocket/de-laval-nozzle] In aerodynamics, the force exerted by the nozzle is defined as the thrust.
